docs.lead_paragraph: An independent federal agency has become one of the most reliable executors of President Biden’s attempts to fight inflation, at a time when the White House has few weapons of its own to quickly bring down stubbornly high prices of consumer staples like groceries.

headline.main: An Emboldened F.T.C. Bolsters Biden’s Efforts to Address Inflation

docs.abstract: Liberals prodded the president for years to blame big corporations for price increases. He is finally doing so, in the grocery aisle.
docs.snippet: Liberals prodded the president for years to blame big corporations for price increases. He is finally doing so, in the grocery aisle.
docs.lead_paragraph: On Super Bowl Sunday, the White House released a short video in which a smiling President Biden, sitting next to a table stocked with chips, cookies and sports drinks, slammed companies for reducing the package size and portions of popular foods without an accompanying reduction in price.

headline.main: Biden Targets a New Economic Villain: Shrinkflation

docs.abstract: Thirty years ago, the U.S. entered an era of productivity gains that enabled healthy growth. Experts are asking if it could happen again.
docs.snippet: Thirty years ago, the U.S. entered an era of productivity gains that enabled healthy growth. Experts are asking if it could happen again.
docs.lead_paragraph: The last time the American economy was posting surprising economic growth numbers amid rapid wage gains and moderating inflation, Ace of Base and All-4-One topped the Billboard charts and denim overalls were in vogue.

headline.main: Are We in a Productivity Boom? For Clues, Look to 1994.

docs.abstract: Beijing’s dominance raises economic and security concerns, and tensions will be high as top climate diplomats meet this week.

docs.lead_paragraph: The world’s two most powerful countries, the United States and China, are meeting this week in Washington to talk about climate change. And also their relationship issues.

headline.main: China Rules the Green Economy. Here’s Why That’s a Problem for Biden.
headline.print_headline: Podesta Meets Beijing’s Climate Envoy Amid Deep Economic Tensions

docs.abstract: The polarization of politics means that rules are imposed, gutted and restored with each election. Experts say that’s bad for the economy.
docs.snippet: The polarization of politics means that rules are imposed, gutted and restored with each election. Experts say that’s bad for the economy.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Biden administration’s move on Thursday to strictly limit pollution from coal-burning power plants is a major policy shift. But in many ways it’s one more hairpin turn in a zigzag approach to environmental regulation in the United States, a pattern that has grown more extreme as the political landscape has become more polarized.

headline.main: How Abrupt U-Turns Are Defining U.S. Environmental Regulations
headline.print_headline: Sharp Reversals Of Climate Rules Hinder Economy

docs.abstract: In a presidential battleground state, electric vehicles have emerged as a contested piece of the economic future — a job-killer or a job-creator.
docs.snippet: In a presidential battleground state, electric vehicles have emerged as a contested piece of the economic future — a job-killer or a job-creator.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last fall, Tiffanie Simmons, a second-generation autoworker, endured a six-week strike at the Ford Motor factory just west of Detroit where she builds Bronco S.U.V.s. That yielded a pay raise of 25 percent over the next four years, easing the pain of reductions that she and other union workers swallowed more than a decade ago.

headline.main: For Michigan’s Economy, Electric Vehicles Are Promising and Scary
headline.print_headline: Are E.V.s Job Killers or Job Creators?

docs.abstract: Much would depend on Congress and the cabinet, but financial forecasters aren’t optimistic.
docs.snippet: Much would depend on Congress and the cabinet, but financial forecasters aren’t optimistic.
docs.lead_paragraph: Speculating about how the economy would perform under a second Donald Trump presidency normalizes the candidacy of a deeply flawed human being. But we’ll all have to live in Trump’s world if he’s elected. So it seems important to talk about the economic outlook under another Trump term.

headline.main: What Would the Economy Look Like Under a Second Trump Term?

docs.abstract: China’s big bet on manufacturing helped to counteract its housing slowdown in the first three months of the year, but other countries are worried about a flood of Chinese goods.
docs.snippet: China’s big bet on manufacturing helped to counteract its housing slowdown in the first three months of the year, but other countries are worried about a flood of Chinese goods.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Chinese economy grew more than expected in the first three months of the year, new data shows, as China built more factories and exported huge amounts of goods to counter a severe real estate crisis and sluggish spending at home.

headline.main: China’s Economy, Propelled by Its Factories, Grew More Than Expected
